For those interested in the same feature in plain old C, have a look at the DSO Howto, section 2.4.2 &quot;Forever const&quot; and the LD flags SHF_MERGE and SHF_STRING.<p>With a little bit of magic, C compilers and linkers are even allowed to turn (simplified example)<p><pre><code>    const char s1[] = &quot;some string&quot;;
    const char s2[] = &quot;string&quot;;
</code></pre>
into<p><pre><code>    const char s1[] = &quot;some string&quot;;
    const char s2[] = s1+5;
</code></pre>
and place these constants in a read-only section shared between multiple loaded instances of the same library or program.

You&#x27;re example is not a static typing issue.  It&#x27;s a feature of the library that the struct field doesn&#x27;t have to have the same name as the form field.<p>I think the issue is more of a DRY thing, which could maybe be fixed with something like:<p><pre><code>    type User struct {
        FirstName string  `form:lowercase_hyphenated`
        LastName  string  `form:lowercase_hyphenated`
    }
</code></pre>
This hypothetical syntax would instruct the library to look for the form fields &quot;first-name&quot; and &quot;last-name&quot;.
